    { q: 'Can AeroPress make real espresso?', a: 'No. Real espresso uses about 9 bars of pressure, and AeroPress does not. What it can make is a strong espresso-style concentrate that works well on its own or in milk drinks.' },
    { q: 'What grind is best for an AeroPress espresso recipe?', a: 'Start fine, around table-salt texture. If the press feels impossible and tastes bitter, go a little coarser. If it rushes through and tastes sour, go a little finer.' },
    { q: 'What is the best AeroPress ratio for espresso-style concentrate?', a: 'A strong starting point is about 18 g of coffee to 55 to 60 g of water. That gives you a short, punchy concentrate you can drink straight, dilute, or mix with milk.' },
    { q: 'How do you fix a sour AeroPress espresso-style shot?', a: 'Change one thing at a time. First grind a little finer. If that does not fix it, add 5 to 10 seconds of steep time. Do not change grind, time, dose, and water all at once or you will learn nothing.' },
