  <Fragment slot="buying-guide">
    <BuyingGuideSection>
      <h2 id="buying-guide">Buying guide: what actually helps AeroPress espresso-style recipes</h2>

      <h3>Start with a good base recipe before buying attachments</h3>
      <p>The standard AeroPress can already make a very good espresso-style concentrate. For most people, that should be the first step. Learn the balanced daily recipe, then decide what you want more of. If you want more body and a no-drip brew chamber, buy the Prismo. If you mostly make milk drinks and want a cleaner workflow, the Flow Control cap makes more sense. If your cups are just bitter and messy, a simpler fix is often fresh paper filters and a slightly gentler grind.</p>

      <h3>If your grind is inconsistent, no recipe will save you</h3>
      <p>This matters more than people want it to. A shaky grinder gives you a mix of powder and boulders, and then your concentrate tastes bitter and sour at the same time. It is like trying to toast bread where half the slices come out pale and the other half catch fire. If your grind is the weak link, I would spend money on the <a href={amazonUrl('B0833SDN8M')} rel="nofollow sponsored noopener" target="_blank">TIMEMORE Chestnut C2 manual grinder</a> before I bought a second attachment. Pair that with our <a href="/posts/best-aeropress-grind-size.html">AeroPress grind size guide</a> and you will make faster progress than by swapping gadgets alone.</p>

      <h3>A scale and kettle make your recipes feel boring in the best way</h3>
      <p>Boring is good here. Boring means repeatable. A small coffee scale stops you from guessing your dose, and a decent kettle helps you stop swinging between too cool and too hot. If you want to tighten the routine even more, read our guides on <a href="/posts/best-aeropress-brew-time.html">AeroPress brew time</a> and <a href="/posts/best-aeropress-brew-temp.html">AeroPress brew temperature</a>. Those two variables do more to clean up bad concentrate than most people expect.</p>

      <h3>Choose the brewer by your real use case</h3>
      <p>The full-size AeroPress Original is still the better pick for most kitchens because it gives you a little more room to work and tweak. The Go is better when space, water, or packability matter more than flexibility. If travel is your main reason for caring about concentrate brewing, read our <a href="/posts/best-aeropress-go-recipe.html">AeroPress Go recipe guide</a>. If you like a stronger cup that you can dilute afterward, the <a href="/posts/best-aeropress-bypass-recipe.html">AeroPress bypass recipe guide</a> is another smart next step.</p>
    </BuyingGuideSection>
